<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">38899991</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2024</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>20</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2024</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>20</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">0894-8275</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>37</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2024</Year><Month>Jun</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>American journal of dentistry</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Am J Dent</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effects of natural products-based dentifrices on acrylic resin for denture bases: A simulated period of 4 years.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>126</StartPage><EndPage>130</EndPage><MedlinePgn>126-130</MedlinePgn></Pagination><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To evaluate the antimicrobial activity of dentifrices based on Malva sylvestris and propolis and the effect on the acrylic resin.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">The inhibitory effect against Candida albicans, Enterococcus faecalis and Streptococcus mutans was determined. The specimens of resin were divided into groups: Control (brushing with distilled water); brushing with Colgate; brushing with Protex; brushing with Malvatricin, brushing with Proporalcare Dental Gel and brushing with Green Propolis Dental Gel. Brushing was carried out in a brushing machine. Roughness and color were assessed. The data were analyzed by ANOVA, followed by the Bonferroni post test (&#x3b1;= 0.05).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">The products evaluated showed antimicrobial activity against all microorganisms (P&lt; 0.05), except Proporalcare Dental Gel, which was not effective against E. faecalis. Greater roughness (P&lt; 0.05) was observed in the samples treated with Colgate. The samples from control and Protex groups showed the lowest color variation and the highest luminosity, with a difference in relation to the others (P&lt; 0.05), which showed higher values, although clinically acceptable.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">The dentifrices based on natural products can be indicated for cleaning prostheses, since they showed antimicrobial activity and did not cause perceptible color changes of the resin tested. The dentifrices did not produce adverse effects on the surface of the resin or did so less than the conventional dentifrice.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright&#xa9;American Journal of Dentistry.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Costa</LastName><ForeName>Marcela S</ForeName><Initials>MS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Biomaterials, School of Dentistry of Uberaba, Uberaba, Minas Gerais, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Fernandes</LastName><ForeName>Marcela S</ForeName><Initials>MS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Biomaterials, School of Dentistry of Uberaba, Uberaba, Minas Gerais, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Oliveira</LastName><ForeName>Viviane D C</ForeName><Initials>VDC</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Dental Materials and Prosthodontics, Ribeir&#xe3;o Preto Dental School, University of S&#xe3;o Paulo, Ribeir&#xe3;o Preto, S&#xe3;o Paulo, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Watanabe</LastName><ForeName>Evandro</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Restorative Dentistry, Ribeir&#xe3;o Preto Dental School, University of S&#xe3;o Paulo, Ribeir&#xe3;o Preto, S&#xe3;o Paulo, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lovato da Silva</LastName><ForeName>Cl&#x915;udia H</ForeName><Initials>CH</Initials><Affiliat